{"id":"cond-mat/9911423","submitter":"Jeff Tallon","authors":"J. L. Tallon, J. W. Loram and G. V. M. Williams","title":"Factors affecting the Optimal Design of High-Tc Superconductors - the\n  Pseudogap and Critical Currents","comments":"9 pages, 8 figures, invited paper ChemHTS workshop, Tokyo Institute\n  of Technology, 15-16 October, to be published Physica C","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/S0921-4534(00)00195-7","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":null,"abstract":"  The impact of the normal-state pseudogap, present in all optimal and\nunderdoped HTS cuprates, on critical currents and critical temperature is\nsurveyed. With the opening of the pseudogap around a doping state of p=0.19 the\ncondensation energy and superfluid density are rapidly suppressed due to\nreduction in the normal-state spectral weight. Even by optimal doping (p=0.16)\nthese measures of the 'strength' of superconductivity are diminished by up to\n40%. This results in a sharp reduction in critical currents and irreversibility\nfield, respectively. The optimal doping state where these properties are\nmaximised is therefore not at maximum Tc but in the lightly overdoped region\nwhere the pseudogap energy falls to zero at p=0.19. The presence of impurities\nand grain boundaries further heightens these effects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 Nov 1999 03:09:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
